-- 03-progressive-crystallization-frames.cell — full eval-one execution trace
--
-- Ready set analysis:
--   task: all givens have ≡ (description, test-inputs, test-expected) → READY
--   solve-soft: needs task→description, task→test-inputs → BLOCKED
--   extract-pattern: needs solve-soft→solution, solve-soft→outputs → BLOCKED
--   crystallize: needs extract-pattern→algorithm → BLOCKED
--   verify-crystal: needs crystallize→hard-body, task→test-inputs, task→test-expected → BLOCKED
--   emit-crystallized: needs verify-crystal→pass-all, verify-crystal→failures,
--                      crystallize→hard-body, §solve-soft → BLOCKED (§ is parse-time, but others aren't)
--
-- Ready set: { task }
-- Dependency chain: task → solve-soft → extract-pattern → crystallize → verify-crystal → emit-crystallized
-- Strictly linear — no parallelism possible. 6 cells, 6 eval-one steps.

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 0: task
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

-- task is a data cell — all yields are determined by givens.
-- No ∴ body needed. Eval-one freezes immediately.

⊢ task
  given description ≡ "Given a list of numbers, return the top 3 largest."
  given test-inputs[] ≡ [
    [7, 2, 9, 4, 1, 8, 3],
    [1, 1, 1, 1, 1],
    [100, 200],
    [5, 3, 8, 1, 9, 2, 7, 4, 6]
  ]
  given test-expected[] ≡ [
    [9, 8, 7],
    [1, 1, 1],
    [200, 100],
    [9, 8, 7]
  ]
  yield description ≡ "Given a list of numbers, return the top 3 largest."
  yield test-inputs ≡ [[7, 2, 9, 4, 1, 8, 3], [1, 1, 1, 1, 1], [100, 200], [5, 3, 8, 1, 9, 2, 7, 4, 6]]
  yield test-expected ≡ [[9, 8, 7], [1, 1, 1], [200, 100], [9, 8, 7]]

  ⊨ test-inputs has same length as test-expected → ✓ (both length 4)
  ⊨ each test-expected entry is sorted descending → ✓

-- Ready set after frame 0: { solve-soft } — task→description and task→test-inputs now bound

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 1: solve-soft
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

-- solve-soft is ⊢ (soft). The LLM interprets the ∴ body.
-- This is the cell that will LATER be crystallized. Right now it runs via LLM.

⊢ solve-soft
  given task→description ≡ "Given a list of numbers, return the top 3 largest."
  given task→test-inputs ≡ [[7, 2, 9, 4, 1, 8, 3], [1, 1, 1, 1, 1], [100, 200], [5, 3, 8, 1, 9, 2, 7, 4, 6]]
  yield solution, outputs[]

  ∴ Solve «task→description». For each input in «task→test-inputs»,
    work through the problem step by step using natural language
    reasoning. Produce the answer for each input.

-- LLM evaluation:
--
-- Input [7, 2, 9, 4, 1, 8, 3]:
--   Sort descending: [9, 8, 7, 4, 3, 2, 1]. Take first 3: [9, 8, 7].
--
-- Input [1, 1, 1, 1, 1]:
--   Sort descending: [1, 1, 1, 1, 1]. Take first 3: [1, 1, 1].
--
-- Input [100, 200]:
--   Sort descending: [200, 100]. Take first 3: only 2 elements, so [200, 100].
--
-- Input [5, 3, 8, 1, 9, 2, 7, 4, 6]:
--   Sort descending: [9, 8, 7, 6, 5, 4, 3, 2, 1]. Take first 3: [9, 8, 7].

  yield solution ≡ "For each input list: sort the numbers from largest to smallest, then take the first 3 elements. If the list has fewer than 3 elements, return all of them in descending order."

  yield outputs ≡ [
    [9, 8, 7],
    [1, 1, 1],
    [200, 100],
    [9, 8, 7]
  ]

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ outputs has same length as test-inputs → ✓ (both 4)
--   ⊨ each output is a list of numbers sorted descending → ✓
--   ⊨ each output has at most 3 elements → ✓

-- KEY: this cell just ran via LLM. It works. But every invocation costs
-- an LLM call. The entire rest of this program exists to ELIMINATE
-- that LLM call by extracting the algorithm and hardcoding it as ⊢=.

-- Ready set after frame 1: { extract-pattern }

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 2: extract-pattern
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

-- extract-pattern is ⊢ (soft). It reads the LLM's solution and
-- extracts the mechanical algorithm. This cell is permanently soft —
-- it's the CRYSTALLIZER, not the thing being crystallized.

⊢ extract-pattern
  given solve-soft→solution ≡ "For each input list: sort the numbers from largest to smallest, then take the first 3 elements. If the list has fewer than 3 elements, return all of them in descending order."
  given solve-soft→outputs ≡ [[9, 8, 7], [1, 1, 1], [200, 100], [9, 8, 7]]
  yield algorithm

  ∴ Read «solve-soft→solution». What deterministic algorithm did you use?
    Express it as a numbered sequence of mechanical steps.

-- LLM evaluation:
-- The LLM reads the natural language solution and extracts:

  yield algorithm ≡ "1. Take input list of numbers. 2. Sort the list in descending order (largest first). 3. Take the first min(3, len(list)) elements. 4. Return the resulting list."

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ algorithm is a numbered list of steps → ✓ (4 numbered steps)
--   ⊨ algorithm contains only deterministic operations → ✓ (sort, take, min, len)
--   ⊨ algorithm does not reference any specific input values → ✓

-- OBSERVATION: the LLM naturally expressed "take first 3 or fewer" as
-- min(3, len(list)). This is already close to ⊢= form. The crystallization
-- gap between what the LLM said in solve-soft and what extract-pattern
-- produces is SMALL for this problem. For harder problems (summarization,
-- creative writing) this gap would be unbridgeable.

-- Ready set after frame 2: { crystallize }

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 3: crystallize
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

-- crystallize is ⊢ (soft). It converts the extracted algorithm into
-- a ⊢= expression. This cell is ALSO permanently soft — it's the
-- code generator. crystallize cannot crystallize ITSELF.
-- (see spec: "crystallize cannot crystallize itself — it is the
-- layer that must stay warm so others can go cold")

⊢ crystallize
  given extract-pattern→algorithm ≡ "1. Take input list of numbers. 2. Sort the list in descending order (largest first). 3. Take the first min(3, len(list)) elements. 4. Return the resulting list."
  yield hard-body

  ∴ Convert «extract-pattern→algorithm» into a single ⊢= expression.

-- LLM evaluation:
-- Maps the 4 steps to a single deterministic expression:
--   step 1: input is «input»
--   step 2: sort(«input», descending)
--   step 3: take(sorted, min(3, len(«input»)))
--   step 4: return

  yield hard-body ≡ "⊢= result ← sort(«input», descending).take(min(3, len(«input»)))"

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ hard-body is a valid ⊢= expression → ✓ (starts with ⊢=, uses ←)
--   ⊨ hard-body contains no natural language → ✓ (only: sort, take, min, len, descending)
--   ⊨ hard-body takes an input list and returns a list → ✓ (takes «input», returns list)

-- THE CRYSTALLIZATION HAPPENED. The LLM just wrote deterministic code
-- that replaces itself. Next step: verify it actually works.

-- Ready set after frame 3: { verify-crystal } — needs hard-body + task→test-inputs + task→test-expected

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 4: verify-crystal
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

-- verify-crystal is ⊢ (soft). It runs the ⊢= expression against
-- test cases. In a real Cell runtime, this would be a hard cell
-- that actually executes the expression. Here we simulate.

⊢ verify-crystal
  given crystallize→hard-body ≡ "⊢= result ← sort(«input», descending).take(min(3, len(«input»)))"
  given task→test-inputs ≡ [[7, 2, 9, 4, 1, 8, 3], [1, 1, 1, 1, 1], [100, 200], [5, 3, 8, 1, 9, 2, 7, 4, 6]]
  given task→test-expected ≡ [[9, 8, 7], [1, 1, 1], [200, 100], [9, 8, 7]]
  yield pass-all, results[], failures[]

  ∴ Apply «crystallize→hard-body» to each input. Compare with expected.

-- LLM evaluation (simulating execution of the ⊢= expression):
--
-- Test 1: input = [7, 2, 9, 4, 1, 8, 3]
--   sort descending: [9, 8, 7, 4, 3, 2, 1]
--   take min(3, 7) = take 3: [9, 8, 7]
--   expected: [9, 8, 7] → ✓
--
-- Test 2: input = [1, 1, 1, 1, 1]
--   sort descending: [1, 1, 1, 1, 1]
--   take min(3, 5) = take 3: [1, 1, 1]
--   expected: [1, 1, 1] → ✓
--
-- Test 3: input = [100, 200]
--   sort descending: [200, 100]
--   take min(3, 2) = take 2: [200, 100]
--   expected: [200, 100] → ✓
--
-- Test 4: input = [5, 3, 8, 1, 9, 2, 7, 4, 6]
--   sort descending: [9, 8, 7, 6, 5, 4, 3, 2, 1]
--   take min(3, 9) = take 3: [9, 8, 7]
--   expected: [9, 8, 7] → ✓

  yield pass-all ≡ true
  yield results ≡ [[9, 8, 7], [1, 1, 1], [200, 100], [9, 8, 7]]
  yield failures ≡ []

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ results has same length as test-inputs → ✓ (both 4)
--   ⊨ failures is empty if and only if pass-all = true → ✓ (failures empty, pass-all true)
--   ⊨ if pass-all then every result matches expected → ✓ (all 4 match)

-- ALL TESTS PASS. The crystal is verified. Substrate transfer can proceed.

-- Ready set after frame 4: { emit-crystallized } — all inputs bound

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- frame 5: emit-crystallized
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

-- emit-crystallized produces the final crystallized cell.
-- This is the climax: the soft cell becomes hard.

⊢ emit-crystallized
  given verify-crystal→pass-all ≡ true
  given verify-crystal→failures ≡ []
  given crystallize→hard-body ≡ "⊢= result ← sort(«input», descending).take(min(3, len(«input»)))"
  given §solve-soft ≡ "(the full definition of solve-soft as a ⊢ cell with ∴ body)"
  yield crystallized-cell, substrate-transfer

  ∴ pass-all is true. Produce the crystallized version of solve-soft.

-- LLM evaluation:
-- The LLM reads §solve-soft (the original soft cell definition) and
-- replaces the ∴ body with the verified ⊢= expression.

  yield crystallized-cell ≡ "⊢= solve-soft ▸ crystallized
  given task→description
  given task→test-inputs
  yield result[]

  ⊢= result ← sort(«input», descending).take(min(3, len(«input»)))

  ⊨ result has at most 3 elements
  ⊨ result is sorted descending"

  yield substrate-transfer ≡ true

-- oracle checks:
--   ⊨ if pass-all then crystallized-cell contains "⊢=" → ✓
--   ⊨ if pass-all then crystallized-cell contains "▸ crystallized" → ✓
--   ⊨ if pass-all then substrate-transfer = true → ✓

-- COMPLETE: 6 cells, 6 eval-one steps. Strictly linear.
-- The program started with a soft cell (solve-soft with ∴) and ended
-- with a hard cell (solve-soft ▸ crystallized with ⊢=).
-- Substrate transfer: ⊢ → ⊢=. The LLM made itself unnecessary.

-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
-- OBSERVATIONS
-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

⊢= obs-substrate-transfer
  given §03-progressive-crystallization
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "SUBSTRATE TRANSFER WORKS: solve-soft started as ⊢ (LLM-evaluated via ∴) and ended as ⊢= (deterministic expression). The program literally replaced an LLM call with a formula. This is the core Cell promise: soft → hard under oracle pressure. The 4 intermediate cells (extract-pattern, crystallize, verify-crystal, emit-crystallized) are the MECHANISM of crystallization. They must stay soft so that solve-soft can go hard."

⊢= obs-crystallization-boundary
  given §03-progressive-crystallization
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "THE CRYSTALLIZER STAYS WARM: extract-pattern, crystallize, and emit-crystallized are permanently soft cells. They use ∴ because their job IS to reason about code — that cannot be mechanized without solving AI. This matches the spec: 'crystallize cannot crystallize itself — it is the layer that must stay warm so others can go cold.' The stem cell analogy holds: these cells are pluripotent (can crystallize anything) but never differentiate themselves."

⊢= obs-easy-problem
  given §03-progressive-crystallization
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "THIS PROBLEM WAS TOO EASY: 'top 3 largest' is trivially crystallizable — sort-then-take is a one-line expression. The gap between ∴ (natural language) and ⊢= (code) was tiny. A more interesting test would be a task where crystallization FAILS: summarization, sentiment analysis, creative writing. The ⊥ path (exhaustion → substrate transfer impossible) is where the real insight lives. This program only tested the happy path."

⊢= obs-oracle-as-test-suite
  given §03-progressive-crystallization
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "ORACLES BECAME A TEST SUITE: the test-inputs/test-expected in task are oracle data. verify-crystal runs them like unit tests. The crystallized cell passes exactly when it matches the oracle expectations. This is the oracle promotion pattern from the spec: when ⊨ says exactly what the output should be, the oracle IS the specification, and the ⊢= expression IS the implementation. Test suite = oracle set. verify-crystal = test runner. crystallize = compiler."

⊢= obs-missing-iteration
  given §03-progressive-crystallization
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "NO RETRY NEEDED: the ⊢= expression passed all 4 test cases on the first try. In a harder problem, verify-crystal would return pass-all = false, and the ⊨? on emit-crystallized would trigger a retry loop: crystallize again with failure context, re-verify. That loop — the PROGRESSIVE part of progressive crystallization — was never exercised. The program name promises iteration but delivers single-shot success. To truly test progressive crystallization, need test cases that force at least one retry."

⊢= obs-meta-pattern
  given §03-progressive-crystallization
  yield observations

  ⊢= observations ← "THE META-PATTERN: this program is a COMPILER written in Cell. task = source code. solve-soft = interpreter. extract-pattern = decompiler. crystallize = code generator. verify-crystal = test runner. emit-crystallized = linker. The soft→hard pipeline mirrors compilation: interpret → analyze → codegen → verify → emit. Cell's contribution: this compiler is itself a Cell program, so it could be applied to ITSELF (crystallize the compiler). But the spec says that's impossible — and this program shows why: the compiler cells must stay soft."
